Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is the softmax function?
AI Response

Softmax converts a vector of raw scores (logits) into probabilities that sum to 1, typically used as the final
activation in multi-class classification models.

Example 1.2

User

What is an autoencoder?
AI Response

An autoencoder learns a compressed (latent) representation of input data through an encoder, then
reconstructs it with a decoder. Used for dimensionality reduction, denoising, and anomaly detection.

Example 1.3

User

What is batch normalization?
AI Response

Batch normalization normalizes layer inputs to have zero mean and unit variance, stabilizing training,
reducing initialization sensitivity, and acting as a mild regularizer.

Example 1.4

User

What is zero-shot learning?
AI Response

Zero-shot learning predicts unseen classes by leveraging semantic relationships or natural language task
descriptions, allowing LLMs to generalize without task-specific training.

Example 1.5

User

What is reinforcement learning?
AI Response

Reinforcement learning trains an agent to make decisions by interacting with an environment and receiving
rewards or penalties, aiming to maximize cumulative reward over time.

Example 1.6

User

What is a neural network?
AI Response

A neural network is a series of algorithms modeled after the human brain, consisting of input, hidden, and
output layers, with weights adjusted during training to minimize prediction error.

Example 1.7

User

What is an RNN?
AI Response



A Recurrent Neural Network processes sequential data with loops allowing information to persist. LSTMs and
GRUs are variants that address the vanishing gradient problem.

Example 1.8

User

What is the bias-variance tradeoff?
AI Response

High bias = underfitting (oversimplified model); high variance = overfitting (over-complex model). Good
models balance both to minimize total prediction error.

Example 1.9

User

What is a convolutional neural network?
AI Response

A CNN uses convolutional layers to automatically learn spatial features from images. Pooling layers reduce
dimensionality. CNNs are the standard for image classification and detection tasks.

Example 1.10

User

What is the ROC curve?
AI Response

The ROC curve plots true positive rate vs false positive rate at various thresholds. AUC (Area Under Curve)
summarizes performance—a perfect model has AUC = 1.0.



